<p>For many people, winning the lottery is a dream come true. If you=E2=80=
=99ve ever imagined what it=E2=80=99d feel like to win the jackpot or what =
you=E2=80=99d do with the financial windfall, we=E2=80=99d bet money that y=
ou probably didn=E2=80=99t account for the sizable tax hit that would also =
come your way.&nbsp;</p>



<p>To help manage your prize money expectations, use our lottery calculator=
 to estimate how much money goes to taxes and what you actually get to keep=
. Additionally, keep reading to learn more about how <a href=3D"https://blo=
g.turbotax.intuit.com/tax-planning-2/how-your-lottery-winnings-are-taxed-41=
882/">lottery winnings</a> are taxed, your options for getting paid, and an=
swers to frequently asked questions.</p>



<p>Looking to report your latest lottery winnings on your annual tax return=
? Use <a href=3D"https://turbotax.intuit.com/personal-taxes/online/">TurboT=
ax</a> to accurately report your windfall.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><strong>How Much Are Lottery Winnings Taxed?=
</strong></h2>



<p>For tax purposes, the IRS considers lottery winnings to be gambling inco=
me, and under the <a href=3D"https://www.irs.gov/instructions/iw2g" target=
=3D"_blank">Internal Revenue Code</a>, they=E2=80=99re subject to federal i=
ncome tax. In addition, lottery winnings may also be taxed at the state lev=
el, but this varies by state. Learn more about federal and state taxes on l=
ottery winnings below.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><strong>Federal Tax on Lottery Winnings</str=
ong></h3>



<p>Any lottery winnings over $5,000 have taxes withheld using the federal w=
ithholding tax rate of <a href=3D"https://www.irs.gov/instructions/iw2g" ta=
rget=3D"_blank">24%</a>. Depending on your prize amount, you may receive a =
<a href=3D"https://turbotax.intuit.com/tax-tips/irs-tax-forms/how-to-use-th=
e-w-2g-tax-form-to-report-gambling-income/L2H5Zy3Yn">Form W-2G, Certain Gam=
bling Winnings</a> from the lottery organization, showing the amount of you=
r winnings and how much tax withheld.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Even with withholding, you must report the full amount of your winnings =
as income on your tax return. Because lottery winnings are included in your=
 total taxable income,, you may be pushed into a higher tax bracket, and ma=
y owe additional tax beyond the amount that was withheld.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Reference the seven tax brackets below or use our <a href=3D"https://tur=
botax.intuit.com/tax-tools/calculators/tax-bracket/">tax bracket calculator=
</a> to see exactly where you fall. The most you=E2=80=99ll be taxed for 20=
25&nbsp;is <a href=3D"https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-provides-tax-inflati=
on-adjustments-for-tax-year-2022" target=3D"_blank">37%</a> for any amount =
over $626,350&nbsp; for 2025 .</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Federal withholding rate for gambling income:</strong> 24%</li>



<li><strong>Federal income tax brackets for single filers in 2025 :</strong=
>
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>If income is $11,925&nbsp; or less: 10%</li>



<li>If income is $11,926 -$48,475 : 12%</li>



<li>If income is $48,476 -$103,350 : 22%</li>



<li>If income is $103,351 -$197,300 : 24%</li>



<li>If income is $197,301 -$250,525 : 32%</li>



<li>If income is $250,526 -$626,350 : 35%</li>



<li>If income is $626,351&nbsp; or more: 37%</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><strong>State Tax on Lottery Winnings</stron=
g></h3>



<p>Depending on your state, your lottery winnings may also be subject to st=
ate income tax. To see the 11 states that have no income tax or don=E2=80=
=99t tax lottery winnings, check out the map below.&nbsp;</p>



<p><strong>States with no income tax:&nbsp;</strong></p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Alaska*</li>



<li>Florida</li>



<li>Nevada*</li>



<li>New Hampshire</li>



<li>South Dakota</li>



<li>Tennessee</li>



<li>Texas</li>



<li>Washington</li>



<li>Wyoming</li>
</ul>



<p><em>*State does not participate in lotteries such as Powerball.</em></p>



<p><strong>States that don=E2=80=99t tax lottery winnings:&nbsp;</strong></=
p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>California</li>
</ul>



<p>It=E2=80=99s important to note that certain states don=E2=80=99t have lo=
tteries at all, but you can always travel across state lines to buy a ticke=
t and win big. Three out of the five states without lotteries will still ta=
x your winnings when you report&nbsp; them as income on your annual tax ret=
urn. These states are Alabama, Hawaii, and Utah.</p>



<p>Although Alaska and Nevada don=E2=80=99t have lotteries, if you buy a ti=
cket in another state, you won=E2=80=99t pay state income taxes on any winn=
ings. On the other hand, two other states, Arizona and Maryland, will withh=
old taxes on your winnings even if you don=E2=80=99t live there.</p>



<p>Whether you=E2=80=99re in a tax-friendly state for lottery income or not=
, read through the next section for how to calculate your taxes depending o=
n which payout you choose.&nbsp;</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><strong>Lottery Payouts: Lump Sum vs. Annuit=
y</strong></h2>



<p>When you win the lottery, you have the choice of receiving your prize as=
 a lump sum or as an annuity. We explain how they=E2=80=99re different and =
the pros and cons of each, so you can pick the right option for you.&nbsp;<=
/p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><strong>Lump Sum</strong></h3>



<p>If you choose to receive your lottery winnings as a lump sum, it means t=
hat you=E2=80=99ll be paid a percentage of the prize all at one time. Gener=
ally, the advertised prize amount refers to the amount paid out if you pick=
 the annuity, and the lump sum amount is specified as a lower =E2=80=9Ccash=
 value=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccash option=E2=80=9D prize.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Typically, the lump sum payout before taxes is about 60% of the advertis=
ed prize, which can help you estimate the value. As a percentage of the jac=
kpot, you=E2=80=99ll receive less money than if you opt for an annuity, but=
 taking the lump sum has its advantages (and disadvantages).</p>



<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Gives the opportunity to invest the money and capitalize on returns mor=
e quickly&nbsp;</li>



<li>Allows for more liquidity over funds so that you have the freedom to us=
e them as you see fit</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Can be challenging to manage a large financial windfall</li>



<li>May lead to bankruptcy or other financial problems if spent too fast</l=
i>



<li>May triple your tax bracket</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>Example calculation of lump sum lottery taxes:</strong></p>



<p>To put this into perspective, let=E2=80=99s say you live in Illinois and=
 win a $1 million jackpot in the lottery. Learn about how you would calcula=
te your estimated taxes and figure out the amount you keep by following the=
 steps below.</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Step 1: Calculate the gross payout.</strong> This is typically =
about 60% of the lottery prize, and you=E2=80=99ll need to apply this to th=
e advertised amount. You can skip this step if you know the =E2=80=9Ccash v=
alue=E2=80=9D amount of the prize and use it as the gross payout in Steps 2=
 and 3.
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Gross payout =3D Advertised prize amount x 0.60</li>



<li>Gross payout =3D $1,000,000 x 0.60</li>



<li><strong>Gross payout =3D $600,000</strong></li>
</ul>
</li>



<li><strong>Step 2: Estimate the total tax withheld.</strong> To do this, y=
ou=E2=80=99ll combine the federal and state tax rates and apply it to the g=
ross payout. For this example, the federal tax rate is 24% and Illinois=E2=
=80=99s tax rate is 4.95%.
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Estimated tax withheld =3D Gross payout x ((federal tax rate + state ta=
x rate) / 100)</li>



<li>Estimated tax withheld =3D $600,000 x ((24 + 4.95) / 100)</li>



<li>Estimated tax withheld =3D $600,000 x (28.95 / 100)</li>



<li>Estimated tax withheld =3D $600,000 x 0.2895</li>



<li><strong>Total estimated tax withheld =3D $173,700</strong> ($144,000 fe=
deral taxes + $29,700 state taxes)</li>
</ul>
</li>



<li><strong>Step 3: Find your take-home winnings.</strong> You can do this =
by subtracting the estimated tax withheld from the gross payout, as shown b=
elow.
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Estimated take-home winnings =3D Gross payout =E2=80=93 tax withheld</l=
i>



<li>Estimated take-home winnings =3D $600,000 =E2=80=93 $173,700</li>



<li><strong>Estimated take-home winnings =3D $426,300</strong></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><strong>Annuity</strong></h3>



<p>Unlike the lump sum award, the annuity pays out your lottery winnings in=
 graduated payments over time. The graduated payments eventually total the =
entire advertised lottery jackpot. It typically starts with an initial paym=
ent followed by graduated annual payments made over 29 years, and you=E2=80=
=99re taxed for this lottery income annually.</p>



<p>For example, the annuity for the <a href=3D"https://www.powerball.com/" =
target=3D"_blank">Powerball</a> jackpot starts with an initial payment, and=
 the payment amount grows by 5% annually for 29 years. This graduated payme=
nt scheme is meant to account for inflation.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Over time, you=E2=80=99ll receive the entire jackpot, but this may come =
with disadvantages depending on future tax rates and how you=E2=80=99d like=
 to use your winnings. Read on to learn about the pros and cons of lottery =
annuities.</p>



<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Offers the option for a steady income over a long period of time that c=
ontinues to earn interest</li>



<li>Defers taxes until the payouts arrive, and may be a benefit if tax rate=
s decline in the future</li>



<li>Reduces the chance of squandering your funds too quickly</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Prevents winners from accessing cash for investments or emergencies</li=
>



<li>May result in losses if tax rates rise in the future</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>Example calculation of annuity lottery taxes</strong></p>



<p>Because lottery jackpots are typically advertised as the annuity amount,=
 you don=E2=80=99t need to estimate the gross payout. You=E2=80=99ll use th=
e exact reward advertised as the jackpot. In this example, you live in the =
state of Illinois and bought a winning lottery ticket with a jackpot of $1 =
million.</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Step 1: Estimate the total tax withheld.</strong> Combine your =
federal and state tax rates and apply it to the prize amount. For this exam=
ple, the federal tax rate is 24% and Illinois=E2=80=99s tax rate is 4.95%.
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Estimated tax withheld =3D Gross payout x ((federal tax rate + state ta=
x rate) / 100)</li>



<li>Estimated tax withheld =3D $1,000,000 x ((24 + 4.95) / 100)</li>



<li>Estimated tax withheld =3D $1,000,000 x (28.95 / 100)</li>



<li>Estimated tax withheld =3D $1,000,000 x 0.2895</li>



<li><strong>Total estimated tax withheld =3D $289,500</strong> ($240,000 fe=
deral taxes + $49,500 state taxes)</li>
</ul>
</li>



<li><strong>Step 2: Find your take-home winnings.</strong> You can do this =
by subtracting the estimated tax withheld from the prize amount.
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Estimated take-home winnings =3D Gross payout =E2=80=93 tax withheld</l=
i>



<li>Estimated take-home winnings =3D $1,000,000 =E2=80=93 $289,500</li>



<li><strong>Estimated take-home winnings =3D $710,500</strong></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>



